ce:section.ce:para:
Here, we have fully investigated the mechanisms (enhanced optical absorption, increased separation of photogenerated carriers and promotion of transfer and storage of photogenerated electrons) by which carbon dots enhance photocatalytic hydrogen production by TiO2. A one-step hydrothermal method was used to load biomass-based carbon dots (Bio-CDs) onto the surface of TiO2 
                     via Ti-O-C bonds (Scheme 1
                     ). The relationships between the morphology and structure of the Bio-CDs/TiO2 and their photochemical and electrochemical properties were thoroughly explored. Both initial hydrogen production and hydrogen production on reuse of the photocatalyst were shown to be improved by doping TiO2 with Bio-CDs through a synergetic interaction of all three mechanisms (enhanced optical absorption, increased separation of photogenerated carriers and promotion of transfer and storage of photogenerated electrons). Additionally, a finite-difference time-domain (FDTD) simulation demonstrated that the Bio-CDs act as electron storage pools in the Bio-CDs/TiO2. This enhances optical absorption and promotes the transfer and storage of photogenerated electrons from TiO2 to the Bio-CDs, thus effectively inhibiting the recombination of electron-hole pairs and enhancing hydrogen production by the photocatalyst.

All of the above results, including the morphology, structure and electrochemical experiments, suggest that the improved photocatalytic hydrogen production by TB9 compared with pristine TiO2 may be due to the unique electron storage characteristics of the Bio-CDs in TB9. An FDTD simulation was used to evaluate the electric field distribution and demonstrate the enhancement of the electric field between TiO2 (
                        Fig. S4
                     ) and Bio-CDs/TiO2 (
                        Fig. S5
                     ). In the simulation, perfectly matched layer boundary conditions were used in the X, Y, Z directions. Incident polarization was vertical along the Z-axis and the direction of the electric field was polarized along the X-axis. In pristine TiO2, when the incident wavelength was 550 nm, there were local “hot spots” in the TiO2 interface region, indicating that a large amount of charge had accumulated at the interface (Fig. 8

                     a). In the Bio-CDs/TiO2, in which Bio-CDs nanoparticles are loaded on the outermost layer of the TiO2, when the incident wavelength was 550 nm, locally enhanced “hot spots” were found in the interface region between TiO2 and Bio-CDs, indicating that a large amount of charge accumulates at the Bio-CDs/TiO2 interface (Fig. 8
                     b). It is worth noting that the electric field intensity of the Bio-CDs/TiO2 is significantly stronger than that of TiO2, confirming that photogenerated electrons are transferred from TiO2 to Bio-CDs and stored. At the same time, optical absorption is also enhanced. The Zeta potentials of TiO2 and Bio-CDs were also measured and found to be 35.22 mV and −3.68 mV, respectively (
                        Fig. S6
                     ). The potential of the Bio-CDs/TiO2 complex (23.87 mV) was significantly lower than that of pristine TiO2 (
                        Fig. S6
                     ), providing strong evidence for transfer of photogenerated electrons to the Bio-CDs.
